lifeSummary":"当James Nugent于大约1794年出生在爱尔兰庫迪 隆福德阿爾達格时，他的父亲Fulke De Nugent22岁，母亲Theffania22岁。他于大约1820年与Bridget Carbery结婚。他们至少是3个儿子的父母。他去世于大约1864年在爱尔兰庫迪 隆福德阿爾達格 安德 莫多福享年72岁。"},"hr":{"ABT 1794–ABT 1864":"oko 1794.–oko 1864.","1794–1864":"1794–1864","1794–1868":"1794–1868","1808–Male":"1808.–preminuo","1821–1893":"1821.–1893","1827–Male":"1827–preminuo","1774–Male":"1774–preminuo","1774–Female":"1774–preminula","ABT 1820":"oko 1820.","ABT 1864":"oko 1864.","May 1827":"svibanj 1827.","1821":"1821.","1798":"1798","1864":"1864","1774":"1774","ABT 1794":"oko 1794.","1893":"1893","1794":"1794","1808":"1808.","1839":"1839","1827":"1827","1868":"1868","1845":"1845","Longford, County Galway, Ireland":"Longford, County Galway, Irska","Ireland":"Irska","Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Irska","County Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Irska","Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh, County Longford, Irska"},"cs":{"ABT 1794–ABT 1864":"okolo 1794–okolo 1864","1794–1864":"1794–1864","1794–1868":"1794–1868","1808–Male":"1808–Zesnulý","1821–1893":"1821–1893","1827–Male":"1827–Zesnulý","1774–Male":"1774–Zesnulý","1774–Female":"1774–Zesnulá","ABT 1820":"okolo 1820","ABT 1864":"okolo 1864","May 1827":"květen 1827","1821":"1821","1798":"1798","1864":"1864","1774":"1774","ABT 1794":"okolo 1794","1893":"1893","1794":"1794","1808":"1808","1839":"1839","1827":"1827","1868":"1868","1845":"1845","Longford, County Galway, Ireland":"Longford, County Galway, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko","Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Irsko","County Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Irsko","Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh, County Longford, Irsko"},"da":{"ABT 1794–ABT 1864":"omkring 1794–omkring 1864","1794–1864":"1794–1864","1794–1868":"1794–1868","1808–Male":"1808–Afdød","1821–1893":"1821–1893","1827–Male":"1827–Afdød","1774–Male":"1774–Afdød","1774–Female":"1774–Afdød","ABT 1820":"omkring 1820","ABT 1864":"omkring 1864","May 1827":"maj 1827","1821":"1821","1798":"1798","1864":"1864","1774":"1774","ABT 1794":"omkring 1794","1893":"1893","1794":"1794","1808":"1808","1839":"1839","1827":"1827","1868":"1868","1845":"1845","Longford, County Galway, Ireland":"Longford, County Galway, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Irland","County Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Irland","Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh, County Longford, Irland"},"nl":{"ABT 1794–ABT 1864":"circa 1794–circa 1864","1794–1864":"1794–1864","1794–1868":"1794–1868","1808–Male":"1808–Overleden","1821–1893":"1821–1893","1827–Male":"1827–Overleden","1774–Male":"1774–Overleden","1774–Female":"1774–Overleden","ABT 1820":"circa 1820","ABT 1864":"circa 1864","May 1827":"mei 1827","1821":"1821","1798":"1798","1864":"1864","1774":"1774","ABT 1794":"circa 1794","1893":"1893","1794":"1794","1808":"1808","1839":"1839","1827":"1827","1868":"1868","1845":"1845","Longford, County Galway, Ireland":"Longford, County Galway, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ierland","County Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Ierland","Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh, County Longford, Ierland"},"en":{"ABT 1794–ABT 1864":"about 1794–about 1864","1794–1864":"1794–1864","1794–1868":"1794–1868","1808–Male":"1808–Deceased","1821–1893":"1821–1893","1827–Male":"1827–Deceased","1774–Male":"1774–Deceased","1774–Female":"1774–Deceased","ABT 1820":"about 1820","ABT 1864":"about 1864","May 1827":"May 1827","1821":"1821","1798":"1798","1864":"1864","1774":"1774","ABT 1794":"about 1794","1893":"1893","1794":"1794","1808":"1808","1839":"1839","1827":"1827","1868":"1868","1845":"1845","Longford, County Galway, Ireland":"Longford, County Galway, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland","County Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Ireland","Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nugent","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin), and northern French: habitational name from any of several places in northern France, such as Nogent-le-Sec and Nogent-sur-Eure (both in Eure), Nogent-le-Phaye, Nogent-le-Roi, and Nogent-le-Rotrou (all in Eure-et-Loir), Nogent-l'Abbesse (Marne), Nogent-l'Artaud (Aisne), and in particular Nogent-sur-Oise (Oise), named with Latin <i>Novientum</i>, apparently an altered form of a Gaulish name meaning ‘new settlement’.","Irish: in Ireland, this is generally the Norman name, but it was also adopted for <b>Mag Uinseanáin</b> (formerly Anglicized as <i>McGunshenan</i>, a variant of   Gilsenan  ), on the grounds of a fancied resemblance between <i>Uinseanán</i> and <i>Uinnseadún</i>.","History: The Anglo-Norman family of this name is descended from Fulke de Bellesme, lord of Nogent in Normandy, who was granted large estates around Winchester after the Conquest. His great-grandson was Hugh de Nugent (died 1213), who went to Ireland with Hugh de Lacy, and was granted lands in Bracklyn, County Westmeath. The family formed itself into a clan on the Irish model, of which the chief bore the hereditary title of <i>Uinsheadun</i> (Irish <i>Uinnseadún</i>), from their original seat at Winchester. They have been Earls of Westmeath since 1621. The name is now a common one in Ireland, and has been adopted there by some who have no connection with the clan."],"variants":[{"name":"Neugent","meanings":["English: variant of   Nugent  ."]},{"name":"Newgent","meanings":["Irish and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Nugent  ."]},{"name":"Nugen","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): variant of   Nugent  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilsenan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colm.","Irish (Meath): shortened form of <b>MacGils(h)enan</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Seanáin</b> ‘son of the servant or devotee of Saint Senan’. Gilsenan has sometimes been Anglicized as   Gilson  , and a northern Irish variant <i>Mag Uinseanáin</i>, formerly Anglicized as <i>McGunshenan</i>, has now been replaced by   Nugent  .   Leonard   has also sometimes been adopted as equivalent."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355932,"age":4,"year":"1798","julianDay":2377767,"description":"Battle of Antrim.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1355933,"age":4,"year":"1798","julianDay":2377767,"description":"The Young Ireland rebellion of 1798 failed.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1355934,"age":45,"year":"1839","julianDay":2392741,"description":"The Night of the BIG WIND. In Killarney and its neighborhood there was a terrible hurricane. The town sustained much damage and many houses were shattered.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1355935,"age":51,"year":"1845","julianDay":2394933,"description":"The Irish Potato Famine. Many Irish emigrate to America. Irish population drops from 8 million to 6 million due to death from starvation or emigration.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When James Nugent was born about 1794, in Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland, his father, Fulke De Nugent, was 22 and his mother, Theffania, was 22. He married Bridget Carbery about 1820. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died about 1864, in Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland, at the age of 72."},"et":{"ABT 1794–ABT 1864":"umbes 1794–umbes 1864","1794–1864":"1794–1864","1794–1868":"1794–1868","1808–Male":"1808–Surnud","1821–1893":"1821–1893","1827–Male":"1827–Surnud","1774–Male":"1774–Surnud","1774–Female":"1774–Surnud","ABT 1820":"umbes 1820","ABT 1864":"umbes 1864","May 1827":"mai 1827","1821":"1821","1798":"1798","1864":"1864","1774":"1774","ABT 1794":"umbes 1794","1893":"1893","1794":"1794","1808":"1808","1839":"1839","1827":"1827","1868":"1868","1845":"1845","Longford, County Galway, Ireland":"Longford, County Galway, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh and Moydow, County Longford, Iirimaa","County Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Iirimaa","Ardagh, County Longford, Ireland":"Ardagh, County Longford, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1794–ABT 1864":"noin 1794–noin 1864","1794–1864":"1794–1864","1794–1868":